   <text>
      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>the Rev. Samuel
            Furly</persName></head>
         <opener><placeName>London</placeName><lb/><date when="1759-02-17">February 17, 1759</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>Dear Sammy,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p><persName><ref target="/persons/pers1206.xml"/>James Kershaw</persName><note
               place="foot" n="1"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers1206.xml"/>James
                  Kershaw</persName> (<date from="1730" to="1797">1730–97</date>), one of
                     <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s first <seg
                  ana="itinerancy">itinerants</seg>, who had withdrawn from riding the circuit; see
               Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 237 or Vickers, <hi rend="italic"
                  >Dictionary</hi>, 190.</note> is an independent minister. Probably, if we live
            till another Conference, he may be in connexion with us. Hitherto he acts as an
            independent. We have no society at <placeName>Kenninghall</placeName>.<note place="foot"
               n="2">Orig., &apos;<placeName>Renninghall</placeName>&apos;; this is surely a
               misprint for <placeName>Kenninghall, Norfolk</placeName>, which was near
                  <placeName>Lakenheath, Suffolk</placeName>, where <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers0763.xml"/>Furly</persName> was placed as curate in late
                  <date when="1758-11">Nov. 1758</date>.</note></p>
         <p>I take <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1589.xml"/>John Pearse</persName> to be an
            honest man. As soon as he sees the truth he will preach it. <persName><ref
                  target="/persons/pers0762.xml"/>Dolly Furly</persName> was considerably better in
            health before I came from <placeName>Bristol</placeName>. And she was all athirst for
            God. I think her soul prospers more and more.</p>
         <p>I will desire Mr. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0806.xml"/>Gilbert</persName><note
               place="foot" n="3"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers0806.xml"/>Nicholas
                  Gilbert</persName>, an <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg> preacher since <date
                  when="1744">1744</date>, was currently stationed in <placeName>London</placeName>,
               and helping care for <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
               />JW</persName>&apos;s publications (see 10:260 in this edn.).</note> to see whether
            the four volumes of the <hi rend="italic">Library</hi> which you mention can be spared.
            And if they can, if they are not necessary for the making up of sets, they will be sent
            with the last <hi rend="italic">Journal</hi> and the <hi rend="italic">Pilgrim&apos;s
               Progress</hi>.<note place="foot" n="4">The books in question are volumes from
                     <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s <hi
                  rend="italic">Christian Library</hi>, installment 9 of his <hi rend="italic"
                  >Journal</hi> (which had just been released), and his abridged republication of
               Bunyan&apos;s <hi rend="italic">Pilgrim&apos;s Progress</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                  >Bibliography</hi>, No. 79).</note></p>
         <p>It is very possible the day of grace may be at end before the day of life is. But I
            believe this is very rarely the case. I have narrowly observed, and have found but one
            indisputable instance in thirty years.</p>
         <p><persName><ref target="/persons/pers0761.xml"/>Nancy</persName><note place="foot" n="5"
                     ><persName><ref target="/persons/pers0761.xml"/>Ann (Bloodworth)
                  Furly</persName>, <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0763.xml"
               />Samuel</persName>&apos;s wife, whom he married in <date when="1758-06">June
                  1758</date>.</note> must give me credit for her letter a little longer, for I am
            at present much straitened for time. <date when="1759-03-01">March 1</date> I hope to be
            at Mr. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers0159.xml"/>Berridge</persName>&apos;s,<note
               place="foot" n="6"><persName><ref target="/persons/pers0159.xml"/>John
                  Berridge</persName> (<date from="1716" to="1793">1716–93</date>), vicar of
                  <placeName>Everton, Bedfordshire</placeName>, had met <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> in <date when="1758">1758</date>,
               and was drawn into the evangelical revival. At this point his parish was a center for
               the work of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s
               preachers in the <placeName>East Midlands</placeName> (see the account of the revival
               in late <date when="1759-05">May 1759</date> in <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s <hi rend="italic"
                  >Journal</hi>, 21:195–200 in this edn.). <persName><ref
                     target="/persons/pers0159.xml"/>Berridge</persName> later embraced Calvinist
               views and attacked <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
               />JW</persName>&apos;s theology. See Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 28;
               and <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>.</note> whence I must strike off for
               <placeName>Colchester</placeName>, so that you will not see me this spring unless you
            come to <placeName>Everton</placeName>. I am, dear Sammy,</p>
         <closer><signed>Yours affectionately,<lb/><persName>J. Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
   </text>
</TEI>
